{"tick": "AAPL", "author": "ChuckJones", "text": "Digging into Apple\u2019s 10-Q can provide additional insights into the company\u2019s performance and outlook. The $29 battery replacement program does not seem to be adding to warranty accruals. The company\u2019s commitments to buy components and products from its vendors increased 40% year over year. The diluted share count could drop by 60 million in the March quarter. Apple\u2019s (NASDAQ: ) 10-Q filing contains a number of financial details that provides additional information about what transpired in the most recent quarter and what the future may hold. When digging into it, you can see what gross margin would be without the accrued warranty expense, which is a \u201ccleaner\u201d number on how much it costs the company to provide its products and services and the operating profit margins for the five geographies. Apple also lets you know what interest rate it actually earns on its cash and investments and how much in components and products it has committed to buy from its manufacturing partners. Apple accrued a significantly lower amount of warranty accruals compared to a year ago. In the December 2016 quarter, there was $2.3 billion of accruals, or 3.0% of revenue. In the latest quarter, the amount was $1.5 billion, or 1.7% of revenue. When you add the company\u2019s warranty accruals back to the reported gross margin, it provides some insight into the cost of producing its products. For the December 2016 quarter, the adjusted gross margin was 41.5% versus last quarter\u2019s 40.1%. There are at least two takeaways from the lower warranty accruals and gross margin. The first is that even with a $999 and $1,149 iPhone X the margins were not higher, as typically, higher-priced items tend to have higher margins. The second is that the battery issue where Apple is . Apple provides details for the operating profit for its five geographic regions. It is worthwhile to monitor the year-to-year trends and, to a lesser degree, which regions are more or less profitable. The total operating margin includes expenses for research & development and various corporate expenses, which the geographies do not. Therefore, the total operating margin is lower when compared to the geographies. The Americas, Japan and Rest of Asia Pacific saw their operating margins decline year over year. Europe and Greater China had increases. Apple\u2019s cash and investments generated $1.45 billion in interest income with a return of 2.11%. Its interest expense increased from $525 million a year ago to $734 million in the December quarter. The company doesn\u2019t provide a blended rate for its interest expense, but when you divide the interest expense into an average of last quarter\u2019s and the current quarter\u2019s debt, it is approximately 2.5%. Apple\u2019s capital plan remained $16 billion for fiscal 2018, of which $2.2 billion was spent in the first fiscal quarter. This compares to $14.9 billion for all of fiscal 2017. Since the company has generated over $63 billion in operating cash flow the past two years, it can easily handle this level of capital expenditure. Apple buys components from its suppliers. In this regard, its 10-Q says, \u201cThe Company utilizes several outsourcing partners to manufacture sub-assemblies for the Company\u2019s products and to perform final assembly and testing of finished products. These outsourcing partners acquire components and build product based on demand information supplied by the Company, which typically covers periods up to 150 days.\u201d A year ago, Apple had committed to buy $24 billion worth of components and products from its suppliers, and at the end of the September quarter, it was $37.6 billion. While it decreased from the September quarter to $33.5 billion at the end of December, it did increase 40% year over year. The higher level may be due to buying components that management thinks may be in tight supply or excess inventory that needs to be worked off. It will probably take a couple of quarters to tell which one it is. I track the number of actual shares that are outstanding about three weeks after the quarter ends to get a feel on what the diluted share count used for the EPS calculation could fall to in the current quarter. It isn\u2019t an exact correlation, but can be fairly accurate. The number of common shares outstanding as of January 19 was 5.074 billion, down 60 million from 5.134 billion on October 20, 2017. Based on historical trends using this is a reasonable decrease in the number of diluted shares in the March quarter. There were 5.158 billion diluted shares in the December quarter, so the March quarter number should be just under 5.1 billion. This is before Apple does a large buyback with its overseas cash that .   I wrote this article myself, and it expresses my own opinions. I am not receiving compensation for it (other than from Seeking Alpha). I have no business relationship with any company whose stock is mentioned in this article. Sand Hill Insights and Chuck Jones are not registered investment advisors (RIAs) or broker/dealers. Readers are advised that the material contained herein should be used solely for informational purposes. Sand Hill Insights/Chuck Jones does not purport to tell or suggest which investment securities readers should buy or sell. Readers should conduct their own research and due diligence and obtain professional advice before making investment decision. Sand Hill Insights/Chuck Jones will not be liable for any loss or damage caused by information obtained in our materials. Readers are solely responsible for their own investment decisions. The chat platform is currently undergoing maintenance. To see the chat, try to refresh in about 5-10 minutes. Chat is not supported in your browser version. Please upgrade your browser or use a different browser, such as Google Chrome. You do not have permissions for this room.", "source": "MarketWatch", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4144277-insights-apples-december-quarter-10-q?source=marketwatch", "headline": "Insights Into Apple's December Quarter 10-Q - Apple Inc. (NASDAQ:AAPL) | Seeking Alpha"}
{"tick": "AAPL", "author": null, "text": "Menu Leading the (NASDAQ: ) rumor mill today is news of a new beta for public testers. Today, we\u2019ll look at that and other for Wednesday. : , reports . The new update brings with it several new features that public beta testers can try out before the final release. The most notable of the features in this beta is battery monitoring. This allows users to monitor the battery life for their smartphone. There is also an option that lets them control performance limiting of the battery. : , notes. According to the document from AAPL, the iPhone 8, iPhone 8 Plus and iPhone X won\u2019t be as affected by battery performance management. The document states that this is due to the devices using a different form of battery management than its older smartphones. However, the company notes that all batteries will still diminish over time and need replaced. : , reports . The new update to the\u00a0watchOS 4.3 beta includes a new charging animation and a portrait orientation when it Nightstand Mode. The beta also brings back the ability to control\u00a0iPhone Music from the device via the Music app. There are also some other changes made in the update. This new update comes out almost two weeks after the first one. Article printed from InvestorPlace Media, https://investorplace.com/2018/02/apple-releases-second-ios-11-3-public-beta/. \u00a92018 InvestorPlace Media, LLC  \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7 \u00b7   \u00b7    Financial Market Data powered by FinancialContent Services, Inc. All rights reserved. Nasdaq quotes delayed at least 15 minutes, all others at least 20 minutes. Copyright \u00a9 2018 InvestorPlace Media, LLC. All rights reserved. 9201 Corporate Blvd, Rockville, MD 20850.", "source": "MarketWatch", "link": "https://investorplace.com/2018/02/apple-releases-second-ios-11-3-public-beta/", "headline": "Wednesday Apple Rumors: Second iOS 11.3 Beta Available to Public Testers | InvestorPlace"}
{"tick": "AAPL", "author": "Bob Brody", "text": "Lost in San Francisco, I asked a 20-something woman for directions. She looked puzzled and peeled off her headphones: \u201cI\u2019m sorry. What did you say?\u201d The same happened with a 30-ish man in Washington: \u201cExcuse me,\u201d he said, unplugging his earbuds. \u201cWhat?\u201d It\u2019s no secret that many people out in public are staring down at a phone screen, divorced from physical reality. They\u2019ve turned a blind eye on the world. Similarly, people wearing some kind of earpiece, cut off from sound, have turned a deaf ear to the world. WSJ Membership Customer Service Tools & Features Ads More", "source": "MarketWatch", "link": "https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-case-against-deliberate-deafness-1518046605", "headline": "The Case Against Deliberate Deafness - WSJ"}
{"tick": "AAPL", "author": "Tomi Kilgore", "text": "Published: By Shares of Apple Inc. and Amazon.com are doing their part to support the broader market, as they have erased early sharp losses to trade higher. Apple's stock was down as much as 1.6% at its intraday low of $158.00, but was now up 0.6% in afternoon trade. Amazon shares were down 3.0% at the intraday low of $1,387.36, but were last up 0.5%. Apple is the largest U.S. company by market capitalization at $821.4 billion while Amazon is the fourth-largest at $696.4 billion. Shares of the second-largest company, Google parent Alphabet Inc. are down 2.7%, while the third-largest company, Microsoft Corp. are down 0.3%. Meanwhile, the tech-heavy Nasdaq 100 is losing 1% and the Dow Jones Industrial Average is shedding 442 points, or 1.7%. Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "source": "MarketWatch", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/apple-amazon-stocks-bounce-sharply-to-swing-into-positive-territory-2018-02-05", "headline": "Apple, Amazon stocks bounce sharply to swing into positive territory - MarketWatch"}
{"tick": "AAPL", "author": "Oleh Kombaiev", "text": "Judging from the PEG multiple, Apple\u2019s price has now approached the fair level. Apple still is overvalued in terms of analysis of internal growth. DCF valuation indicates a moderate potential for further growth of Apple. A comprehensive valuation of Apple (NASDAQ: ) after the publication of the last quarter results allows one to expect only the neutral dynamics of the company's value in the nearest quarter. First, let\u2019s take a quick look at the dynamics of total return. Including the current February result, the total return of Apple\u2019s shares has been showing a negative result and a downtrend over the last three months. The current month\u2019s returns are within the bounds of natural volatility so far, but frankly, the situation does not inspire optimism. Now, let\u2019s look at Apple\u2019s multiples. Given the uniqueness of Apple\u2019s business model and the stage of its life cycle, I consider it inappropriate to directly compare the multiples of Apple with those of other companies, simply because Apple doesn\u2019t have direct competitors. In this case, in my opinion, the most optimal multiples are the P/E and P/S adjusted for the projected growth in profits and revenues, respectively. For the first comparison, I took Alibaba (NYSE: ) and the companies from the FAAMG list. Here's what I got: And, here is the of a similar comparison at the end of November 2017: Judging by the P/S to growth (forward) multiple, Apple remains significantly overvalued, although the situation has somewhat improved over two months. But the investors are hardly inclined to evaluate Apple based on its revenue growth. As for the P/E to growth (forward) multiple, it indicates that Apple\u2019s shares are now, unlike two months ago, almost perfectly balanced. It happened mainly because the consensus of analysts\u2019 regarding the growth of Apple\u2019s EPS in the period from 2018 to 2019 rose from 7% in November to the current 11%. If you compare Apple to a broader list of companies using this method, the result is more optimistic: judging by the P/E to growth (forward), Apple even has a slight potential for growth: Let's move on and look at how the growth of Apple's financial indicators relate to the current level of its multiples. In the Q4, the EPS of Apple grew by 16.25% YOY, and it is the fastest growth rate for the last eight quarters. However, the long-term trend remains disappointing: in the Q4, the three-year CAGR EPS totaled 9.46% - this is the worst result in its history. At the same time, the P/E is still at the level of the year 2017 and substantially above the median. We record the company\u2019s reassessment here. The situation with the EBITDA is similar. In the O4, the four-year CAGR of EBITDA amounted to the minimum historical value. However, the EV/EBITDA remains above the median. Note that matching of the CAGR of EBITDA with the EV/EBITDA has a distinct wave nature. Judging from the cycle, the EV/EBITDA is now at the top of yet another wave. The growth rates of Apple\u2019s OpFCF in the last quarter is not significantly higher than those in other 2017 quarters. However, the EV/OpFCF stays near the maximum levels for the past seven years. Let\u2019s look at Apple\u2019s capitalization from the different angle. In the Q4, Apple\u2019s ROE amounted to the maximum value in the year 2017. At the first glance, it is not bad. However, the P/BV multiple remains substantially higher than its balanced values within the dependencies between the specified indicators. Assuming that the observed drop in Apple prices continues, the capitalization of Apple will drop to $720 billion before the P/BV reaches a balanced level. As we can see, in the Q4, the long-term growth rate of the key financial indicators of Apple continued to slow down. However, the main company\u2019s multiples, although slightly declined, are still above their median values. Now, let's see what the DCF analysis says about the fair price of Apple. you can find a detailed description of the DCF model I built for Apple. Now, I will only update the calculations. First of all, it should be noted that after the publication of the Q4 results, the analysts have slightly lowered Apple's revenue forecast for the next two years. Here's what they were like in November 2017: Here's what they look like now: Therefore, I\u2019ve adjusted my 10-year forecast of Apple\u2019s revenue: Here is the WACC calculation: The current 1-y Beta Coefficient of Apple is 1.1, which is still substantially above the median, but below the peaks demonstrated at the beginning of 2018: I assume that Apple's operating margin will gradually decrease to the level of 18% due to the increased competition. So, here's the model itself: The DCF-based target price of Apple's shares is $191, The observed decline in Apple\u2019s value amidst the fall of the entire U.S. stock market has benefited Apple, and, judging by the multiples, the company is now close to its balanced state. The key financial indicators of Apple demonstrated acceleration in the Q4, but it may be only a one-time success because the long-term trends remain negative. Apple\u2019s Beta Coefficient demonstrates a decrease, which has a positive impact on the DCF valuation of the company. However, the 18% growth potential cannot be called impressive. As I\u2019ve mentioned in my previous articles ( , ), I still believe that in the coming quarters, Apple's shares will move sideways in the best case scenario, because the lack of confident signs of the company\u2019s accelerating growth runs counter to its chronically overestimated multiples.   I wrote this article myself, and it expresses my own opinions. I am not receiving compensation for it (other than from Seeking Alpha). I have no business relationship with any company whose stock is mentioned in this article. The chat platform is currently undergoing maintenance. To see the chat, try to refresh in about 5-10 minutes. Chat is not supported in your browser version. Please upgrade your browser or use a different browser, such as Google Chrome. You do not have permissions for this room.", "source": "MarketWatch", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4144320-apple-valuation-update-quarterly-results?source=marketwatch", "headline": "Apple: Valuation Update After Quarterly Results - Apple Inc. (NASDAQ:AAPL) | Seeking Alpha"}
